---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '../components/Breadcrumb.astro';
---

<Layout title="About ‚Äî TroySkills" description="Learn about TroySkills, the open-source AI agent security database. Mission, team, roadmap, and FAQ.">
  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <Breadcrumb items={[{ label: "About" }]} />
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">About TroySkills</h1>

    <div class="prose prose-invert prose-red max-w-none prose-p:text-slate-300 prose-headings:text-slate-100 prose-a:text-red-400 prose-strong:text-slate-200">

      <!-- Mission -->
      <div class="not-prose bg-slate-900 border border-red-500/20 rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-400 mb-2">Our Mission</h2>
        <p class="text-slate-300 text-lg leading-relaxed">To create the definitive public database of AI agent attack patterns, enabling developers and security teams to understand, detect, and defend against malicious AI agent skills before they cause harm.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Why This Exists</h2>
      <p>
        AI agents are becoming more capable and more autonomous. They install skills, run code, 
        access APIs, send messages, and manage infrastructure. This power creates a new attack 
        surface: <strong>malicious skills</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        A malicious skill can hijack an agent's behavior, steal credentials, exfiltrate data, 
        or compromise the host system ‚Äî all while appearing to provide legitimate functionality.
      </p>
      <p>
        The security community has CVE for software vulnerabilities and NVD for their analysis. 
        But there's no equivalent for AI agent skills. <strong>TroySkills fills that gap.</strong>
      </p>

      <h2>Project History</h2>
      <p>
        TroySkills was conceived in early 2026 as a response to the rapid proliferation of AI agent frameworks 
        without corresponding security documentation. As agents gained the ability to install third-party skills, 
        execute code, and interact with external services, the attack surface expanded dramatically ‚Äî but there was 
        no centralized resource documenting the threats.
      </p>
      <p>
        The project launched with 100 documented attack patterns across 7 categories, covering everything from 
        basic prompt injection to sophisticated supply chain attacks. It is designed to grow with community contributions.
      </p>

      <h2>What We Track</h2>
      <p>We document attack patterns across 7 categories:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>P1 ‚Äî Prompt Injection:</strong> Skills that override agent system prompts</li>
        <li><strong>P2 ‚Äî Data Exfiltration:</strong> Skills that steal data and credentials</li>
        <li><strong>P3 ‚Äî Privilege Escalation:</strong> Skills that gain elevated access</li>
        <li><strong>P4 ‚Äî Malicious Scripts:</strong> Skills containing malware</li>
        <li><strong>P5 ‚Äî Config Tampering:</strong> Skills that poison agent configuration</li>
        <li><strong>P6 ‚Äî Social Engineering:</strong> Skills that abuse messaging capabilities</li>
        <li><strong>P7 ‚Äî Supply Chain:</strong> Skills that exploit the distribution chain</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Team -->
      <h2>Team</h2>
      <div class="not-prose bg-slate-900 border border-slate-800 rounded-xl p-6 mb-6">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-4">
          <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-red-500 to-orange-500 flex items-center justify-center text-white text-xl font-bold">GC</div>
          <div>
            <div class="font-semibold text-lg">Guangyu Chen</div>
            <div class="text-sm text-slate-400">Project Creator & Lead</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mb-4">TroySkills is created and maintained by Guangyu Chen. The project leverages AI-assisted research and analysis to systematically document and categorize AI agent attack patterns at scale.</p>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xs text-slate-500">
          <span class="px-2 py-1 bg-slate-800 rounded">ü§ñ AI-Assisted Research</span>
          <span class="px-2 py-1 bg-slate-800 rounded">üë§ Human-Verified</span>
          <span class="px-2 py-1 bg-slate-800 rounded">üåê Open Source</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Roadmap -->
      <h2>Roadmap</h2>
      <div class="not-prose space-y-4 mb-8">
        <div class="bg-slate-900 border border-green-500/30 rounded-xl p-5">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded-full bg-green-500/20 text-green-400 font-medium">‚úÖ Complete</span>
            <span class="font-semibold">Phase 1: Database Foundation</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">100 attack patterns across 7 categories. Full website with search, API, severity scoring, defense guide, and timeline views. RSS feed and structured data.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-slate-900 border border-yellow-500/30 rounded-xl p-5">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded-full bg-yellow-500/20 text-yellow-400 font-medium">üîÑ In Progress</span>
            <span class="font-semibold">Phase 2: Community & Contributions</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">GitHub issue templates for pattern submission. Community review process. Expert advisory panel. Integration with existing security databases and frameworks.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-slate-900 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded-full bg-slate-600/50 text-slate-400 font-medium">üìã Planned</span>
            <span class="font-semibold">Phase 3: Automated Scanning</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">Automated skill scanning tools. CI/CD integration for detecting malicious patterns. Agent framework plugins. Real-time threat intelligence feed.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>How to Contribute</h2>
      <p>
        TroySkills is open source. Report new attack patterns, submit pull requests, 
        or help improve existing entries on 
        <a href="https://github.com/cgyagenticloud/troyskills">GitHub</a>.
      </p>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      
      <h3>Is TroySkills affiliated with MITRE, NIST, or OWASP?</h3>
      <p>No. TroySkills is an independent project. We are inspired by the CVE/NVD model and MITRE ATT&CK framework, but we are not affiliated with any of these organizations.</p>

      <h3>Are these real attacks or theoretical?</h3>
      <p>Both. Some patterns are based on documented real-world incidents, while others are derived from security research and represent realistic attack scenarios. Each entry notes whether it's based on observed or theoretical attack vectors.</p>

      <h3>Can I use TroySkills data in my own projects?</h3>
      <p>Yes. The database is open source and available via our <a href="/api">REST API</a>. We encourage integration into security tools, agent frameworks, and research projects.</p>

      <h3>How do I report a new attack pattern?</h3>
      <p>Open a <a href="https://github.com/cgyagenticloud/troyskills/issues/new?template=new-pattern.md">GitHub issue</a> using our template, or submit a pull request directly. See our <a href="/contribute">contribution guide</a> for details.</p>

      <h3>How is severity determined?</h3>
      <p>We use a scoring system based on impact, exploitability, and scope ‚Äî similar to CVSS but adapted for AI agent contexts. See our <a href="/scoring">scoring methodology</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <h2>Disclaimer</h2>
      <p>
        This database is for <strong>defensive security research only</strong>. 
        All attack patterns are documented to help the community build better defenses. 
        Do not use this information for malicious purposes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
